STEP 4 — OVERALL VERDICT
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

A pair PASSES under either of two paths. Quarterly results do NOT determine the verdict.

PATH 1 (standard):
  5yr primary p < 0.05
  AND 2yr primary p < 0.05
  AND both primary regressions run in the SAME direction
    (e.g. both A→B, or both B→A).

  If 5yr passes A→B but 2yr passes B→A, the directions are inconsistent — the pair does
  NOT pass Path 1. A genuine long-run relationship should remain in the same causal
  direction across both windows.

PATH 2 (post-break):
  Post-break EG re-test passes (at least one direction p < 0.05 in Step 6)
  AND the ZA-detected structural break date was more than 2 years before today.

  The 2-year floor ensures sufficient history exists in the new regime to trust the
  post-break estimate. If the break is less than 2 years old, the post-break window is
  too short to confirm a durable new relationship.

Display: three-column row (5yr ✓/✗ + direction | 2yr ✓/✗ + direction | direction match ✓/✗)
→ final PASS/FAIL banner indicating which path was satisfied (or why it failed).
Footnote: quarterly reference count.


