STEP 5 — STABILITY DIAGNOSTICS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Two charts computed separately from the EG tests, both using 5-year history in the primary
direction (lower 5yr p-value).

─── Rolling β Chart ────────────────────────────────
Rolling 252-day OLS β for log(Y) = α + β · log(X):
  At each date t: regress log(Y_{t-251:t}) on log(X_{t-251:t}) → record β_t.

Chart shows:
  - Rolling β line over 5 years
  - 5yr OLS β (from Step 2a primary) as a red dashed reference line
  - ±1σ bands of the rolling β distribution (gray dotted)
Summary metrics: 5yr OLS β | Rolling mean | Rolling std | Range (min → max)

Purpose: reveal hedge ratio volatility, structural breaks, regime shifts.

─── Rolling EG P-Value Chart ───────────────────────
Rolling 252-day EG p-value: at each date t, run OLS + adfuller(residuals) on the trailing
252-day window. Plot the resulting p-value series over 5 years.

Chart shows:
  - Rolling EG p-value line
  - Red dashed threshold at 0.05
  - Vertical dotted line at the ZA-detected break date (if any)
Caption under chart explains the ZA cut-off date:
  "This is not the point where the relationship diverges the most. It is the point where
   the relationship changes most abruptly — the sharpest bend in the spread series. The ZA
   test finds this by trying every date as a potential break point and selecting the one where
   allowing a level shift there produces the strongest evidence of stationarity on both sides."

Purpose: show when cointegration was active vs. broken over time.
Note: uses plain adfuller (not MacKinnon 2010 EG table) for computational efficiency —
this chart is for trend visualisation only, not for final PASS/FAIL decisions.


━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
STEP 6 — STRUCTURAL BREAK ANALYSIS
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Purpose: identify whether a full-window FAIL is caused by a temporary structural event
rather than a permanent absence of cointegration; if so, test whether the pair is cointegrated
in the post-break regime.

─── Break period identification ────────────────────
Scan the rolling EG p-value series for contiguous stretches where p > 0.05.
Filter to stretches ≥ 30 calendar days (shorter ones treated as noise).
Sort by duration; display chronologically with the longest marked as "main break".

─── Zivot-Andrews structural break test ────────────
Run zivot_andrews(residuals, regression='c', autolag='t-stat') on the 5yr primary residuals.
The ZA test tries every candidate date in the interior of the sample and selects the one
where allowing a one-time level shift produces the most negative ADF statistic — i.e. the
sharpest bend in the spread, not the point of maximum divergence.

Report: ZA stat, p-value, detected break date.
If ZA p < 0.05: formally detected — show amber warning with break date.
If ZA p ≥ 0.05: candidate date shown with info note; post-break re-test still runs.

─── Post-break EG re-test ──────────────────────────
Start date = ZA-detected break date.
Run full EG in BOTH directions on data from break_date → today:
  - Fresh OLS per direction (re-estimates α and β from the post-break window)
  - adfuller(residuals, autolag='AIC') → p-value
  - ★ primary = lower post-break p-value
  - Show α, β, ADF stat, p-value, crit 5%, N obs for each direction
  - Verdict: Cointegrated ✓ or ✗ per direction

If either direction passes (p < 0.05) AND ZA break date > 2 years ago:
  "Qualifies for Path 2 PASS — post-break cointegration confirmed with sufficient history."
If either direction passes but ZA break date ≤ 2 years ago:
  "Post-break cointegration detected but the break is too recent — does not yet qualify
   for Path 2 PASS. Re-check once the new regime has 2+ years of data."
If both directions fail:
  "Break appears to be a permanent regime shift."

Minimum 60 observations required; otherwise show "insufficient data" notice.

─── AI Break Period Commentary ─────────────────────
On-demand button: "Generate Commentary (AI)"
Triggers only when at least one break period ≥ 30 days has been identified.
Result is cached in st.session_state[f"break_commentary_{A}_{B}"] and survives reruns.

Agent design → see `break_commentary.py` section in PLAN.md for full prompt and logic.


